Understanding the RDS CAL Model – Detailed and Descriptive Explanation (Exam-Oriented)
Remote Desktop Services (RDS), developed by Microsoft, uses a structured licensing system known as the RDS CAL (Client Access License) model. This model is designed to ensure that only authorized users or devices can access remote desktops and applications hosted on a server. It also helps organizations stay compliant with licensing rules while efficiently managing access.

1. Concept of the RDS CAL Model
The RDS CAL model is based on the idea that every user or device connecting to a Remote Desktop Session Host must have a valid license. These licenses are managed by a Remote Desktop Licensing Server, which acts as a central authority.
Detailed Working Process
When a user or device attempts to connect to a session host, the system first checks whether a license is required.
If required, the session host communicates with the licensing server.
The licensing server checks its available pool of licenses.
If a valid license (CAL) is available, it is issued to the user or device.
Once the license is assigned, the user is allowed to access the remote desktop or applications.
👉 In simple terms, the licensing system works like a verification checkpoint, ensuring that only authorized connections are allowed.
2. Types of RDS CALs (Detailed Explanation)
There are two main types of RDS CALs, and the choice depends on how users access the system.
A. Per Device RDS CAL
Description
In this model, the license is assigned to a specific physical device rather than a user. Any person using that device can access the remote system.
Detailed Features
The license is permanently linked to the device hardware
It is fully tracked and managed by the licensing server
It works even if the device is not part of an Active Directory domain
A temporary license is issued when the device connects for the first time
Detailed Working Process
When a device connects for the first time, it receives a temporary license valid for 90 days.
After successful login and validation, the licensing server upgrades it to a permanent license, provided licenses are available.
If no permanent license is available, the temporary license continues until it expires.
Each time the device connects, the server checks the license validity and expiry date.
Before expiry (within 7 days), the license is automatically renewed for a period of 52 to 89 days.
Additional Characteristics
Up to 20% of licenses can be revoked and reassigned
Over-allocation is not allowed
Provides strict control over device access
Use Case
This model is ideal in environments where multiple users share the same computer, such as:
Schools and computer labs
Call centers with shift-based employees
Public access systems
B. Per User RDS CAL
Description
In this model, the license is assigned to a specific user account rather than a device. The user can connect from multiple devices.
Detailed Features
The license is linked to a user in Active Directory
The same user can access the system from different devices
Licensing is not strictly enforced by the system
Administrators are responsible for ensuring compliance
Detailed Working Process
When a user connects, a license is assigned from the available pool.
The license appears to have a validity of 60 days.
Each time the user logs in, the expiration date is extended by another 60 days.
If the user does not log in before expiration, the license is removed from the list.
The next login creates a new license entry.
Additional Characteristics
No temporary license mechanism
Cannot be revoked manually
Can be over-allocated (risk of license violation)
Typically reassigned after a minimum of 90 days
Use Case
Best suited for environments where:
Each user has their own personal device(s)
Employees work remotely or use multiple devices
3. Detailed Comparison of Per Device vs Per User CALs
Feature	Per Device CAL	Per User CAL
Assignment	Device-based	User-based
Access	Multiple users on one device	One user on multiple devices
Tracking	Strictly tracked	Less strictly enforced
Temporary License	Available (90 days)	Not available
Renewal	Automatic (52–89 days)	Extended on login (60 days)
Revocation	Allowed (up to 20%)	Not allowed
Over-allocation	Not possible	Possible
Best Environment	Shared devices	Individual users
4. Licensing Grace Period
When Remote Desktop Services is first installed, there is a 120-day grace period.
During this time, users can connect without a licensing server.
After the grace period ends:
A valid licensing server is required
Users must have valid CALs to connect
👉 This grace period allows administrators time to configure licensing properly.
5. Cross-Domain and Workgroup Licensing
A licensing server can issue licenses across:
Multiple Active Directory domains
Forests
Workgroup environments
👉 However, certain limitations exist, especially in tracking per user licenses in workgroups.
6. License Tracking and Administration
Administrators use tools like Remote Desktop Licensing Manager to:
Monitor license usage
Generate reports
Ensure compliance with licensing agreements
👉 This is especially important for per user licensing, where enforcement is not automatic.
7. RDS CAL Version Compatibility (Very Important)
Key Rules
Older licenses cannot be used for newer server versions
Newer licenses can be used for older server versions
Example
A Windows Server 2022 CAL can connect to 2022 or older servers
It cannot connect to a newer version like 2025
👉 Compatibility must be checked between:
CAL version
Session Host version
License Server version
8. License Server Compatibility
CALs must be installed on a compatible license server
A license server must support the version of CAL being installed
👉 Example:
2022 CALs can be installed on 2022 or earlier compatible servers
Cannot be installed on incompatible older versions
9. Practical Use Cases (Combined Understanding)
Per Device Model
Schools with shared lab computers
Offices with shift-based employees
Public kiosks
Per User Model
Corporate offices with personal laptops
Remote work environments
Organizations with flexible working setups
